observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed that the

(a) City Treasurer to

(i) strictly monitor the implementation of the action plan on conducting public auction and issuance of warranty of levy as remedies for the collection of delinquent real property taxes as provided in Section 256 of R.A. 7160;

(ii) timely prepare an updated Certified List of Taxpayers and Taxes Due and submit the same to the Accounting Office as the basis in setting up of RPT/SET receivables in the books of accounts of the City at the beginning of the year;

(b) City Accounting Office and City Treasurer’s Office (CTO) to reconcile their records of RPT/SET receivables in order to report reliably the said accounts in the financial statements;

(c) Acting City Accountant to observe the provision under Section 42 of Government Accounting Manual (GAM) for LGUs Volume 1 by using the Certified List of Taxpayers and Taxes Due prepared by the CTO as the basis in recording the receivables at the beginning of the year; and

(d) City Assessor to coordinate and timely provide the  CTO with the needed assessment reports to facilitate the preparation of Certified List of Taxpayers by the latter within the prescribed period.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed that the

(a) Inventory Committee in coordination with City General Services Office (CGSO) and all the department heads and offices to exert extra effort to complete the physical inventory of all Property, Plant and Equipment (PPEs) of the City Government and reconcile the report with the accounting records;

(b) CGSO to

(i) strictly comply with the required maintenance of complete and updated property records; 

(ii) observe the annual submission of the physical inventory reports on PPEs to the Office of the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to Section 266 of Government Accounting Manual (GAM) for LGUs Volume 1 for timely review and validation;

(iii) immediately notify the Auditor and submit the required documents for Request for Relief of Accountability within the deadline, whenever a loss of property happens;

(c) Acting City Accountant to 

(i) coordinate with the CGSO and Inventory Committee for the reconciliation of respective records and effect the necessary corrections/adjustments, if warranted, in the books of accounts; and

(ii) transfer the completed projects from the Construction in Progress (CIP) account to appropriate asset accounts.

We recommend and the Local Chief Executive agreed that the

(a) Accounting Office to exert more effort in determining the nature and details of the long-outstanding bank reconciling items amounting to ₱106,393.90 to facilitate the immediate adjustments of the same in the book of accounts; 

(b) City Treasurer in coordination with the concerned departments who are in charge of expropriation proceedings to follow up its status with the concerned trial courts to determine whether the claims are still valid since the deposits for the purpose is non-moving for more than 10 years and to further determine the possibility of transferring the said deposits to Government Financial Institutions (GFIs).

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct

(a) City Budget Officer to provided explanation/justification on the purchase of laboratory and other medical supplies which was charged to budget for various commodities for relief operations as approved by the Sangguniang Panlungsod (SP) under the Supplemental Budget (SB) No. 04 series of 2020;

(b) City Health Office to determine the necessity of purchasing additional ventilators as approved by the SP under the SB No. 04 series of 2020, otherwise consider the realignment/reprogram of the unimplemented project; 

(c)  Bids and Awards Committee to

(i) ensure that the Purchase Orders executed and conformed by the suppliers are compliant with GPPB Circular 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020 for the purchase of goods;

(ii) submit proof of posting of updated Annual Procurement Plan (APP) and Notice of Award in GPPB online portal on the noted procurement; 

d) City Accounting Office to 

(i) attach brochures/photographs of supplies/materials purchased as required by Section 9.1.3.1 of COA Circular 2012-001dated June 14, 2012;

(ii) consistently record the laboratory and medical supplies purchased as Inventory following the Perpetual Inventory Method; 

(e) City Social Welfare and Development Office to

(i) prepare schedule of inventory of donations in the required format and submit within ten (10) working days after the end of each quarter to the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC), through the Office of the Civil Defense (OCD), copy furnished the respective COA Auditors as required in Section II (a) and (b) of COA Circular No. 2020-009;

(ii) utilize the unused cash donation amounting to ₱30,000.00 received from private donor for COVID-19 related PPAs;

(iii) submit distributions list/acknowledgment receipts on the rice given to various groups/institution/sector for random validation of the Audit Team;

(iv) submit report/certification on the consumption of dressed chicken in the community kitchen with details such as the dates consumed and list of volunteers/frontliners given with meals

(v) submit distribution lists/list of recipients of food packs given to other beneficiaries aside from households.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed that the

(a) Chairman, Bids and Awards Committee to

(i) ensure that the necessary procurement information are timely posted in Government Procurement Policy Board (GPPB) portal and PhilGEPS;

(ii) utilize the City’s website in the posting of procurement opportunities and information;

(iii) include warranty clause in the Purchase Order and require all suppliers to submit Omnibus Sworn Statement in accordance with Guidelines for Emergency Procurement under Bayanihan to Heal as One Act; and

(b) Acting City Accountant to observe the proper recognition in the books of the procured equipment and inventory in accordance with Section 175, Chapter 6 and Section 208, Chapter 7, Volume 1 of Government Accounting Manual for LGUs.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Social Welfare Development Officer to

(a) provide justification/explanation on the exclusion in Social Amelioration Card (SAC) master list of some paid beneficiaries of Social Amelioration Program (SAP);

(b) submit justification/explanation on the non-issuance of Official Receipts to all beneficiaries who returned the received SAP and copies of the Acknowledgment Receipts; 

(c) submit copy of report/information/certification whether those 18 beneficiaries who are members of 4Ps as listed in the SAC master list were evaluated to ensure that no duplication of assistance was given; and

(d) submit copy of report/information/certification that the ten respondents who did not confirm on what criteria/sector they belong in the questionnaire of the Audit Team were evaluated to be qualified as SAP beneficiaries.

We reiterated our recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to  instruct the Head of the General Services Office and the Inventory Committee to (a) cause the immediate correction and completion of required data in  the updated Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP); 

(b) coordinate with the accounting office for reconciliation of their respective records and effect the necessary adjustments, if any, in the books of the agency; 

(c) prepare/complete the corresponding assessment, evaluation and appraisal reports; 

(d) once the request for disposal is approved by COA,  undertake prompt disposal of the subject properties to prevent further deterioration and decline of value in order to immediately generate additional funds from sale thereof; and 

(e) for the succeeding years, ensure submission to the Office of the LCE, for approval, the schedule of disposal of unserviceable assets and those beyond economical repairs at least yearly, to prevent   the recurrence of similar lapses.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct:

The City Accountant-

in coordination with the CSWDO, effect the reconciliation of account balance with that Office and accordingly enter the necessary adjustment/correction, if any, in the accounting reports and records.

issue follow-up demand letters to the persons accountable/liable for the recovery of the outstanding receivables;

exhaust all possible remedies/actions for the recovery of the subject receivables and, if warranted, file appropriate request for a possible write-off of dormant accounts; and

The City Social Welfare Development Officer (SWDO) to-

revisit the Memorandum of Agreement governing the implementation of SEA program and ensure that the provisions stipulated therein are strictly observed in order to protect the interest of the government;

issue follow-up/series of  demand letters to the delinquent borrowers requiring them to pay in accordance with the scheduled amortization to recover the overdue receivables; 

conduct monitoring and post–evaluation on the status and result of the project; and

in coordination with the Accounting Office, effect the reconciliation of account balance with that Office and accordingly enter the necessary adjustment/correction in the corresponding reports and records.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct-

The Offices/Unit Heads concerned to:

provide competent documents, such as detailed work plan  for the particular Saturdays and the corresponding validated accomplishment report  that would corroborate on the management’s assertion that the individuals under the JO contracts actually reported for work during additional workdays (Saturdays) as reflected in the Daily Time Records (DTRs);

keep, maintain records of the job order individuals assigned in their respective units, such as the daily attendance log book and record of daily accomplishments. Utilize the same as reference in checking the correctness of the Daily Time Records (DTRs) and accomplishments being submitted by the subject workers;

The City Accountant to (a) ensure that review on the completeness of supporting documents on claims for the payment of wages are thoroughly reviewed, particularly for additional work days of individuals under the job order contracts; and 

The City Human Resource Management Officer to submit explanation and/ or justification on the inclusion of Saturdays and Holidays as additional regular workdays for the selected individuals whose work designation are administrative and office work in nature. Further, timely provide the Office of the Auditor with copy of approved job order contracts to facilitate timely review and evaluation.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive directed the-

City Treasurer to adopt more efficient procedures to ensure that all payment will be immediately release to the respective claimants in order to facilitate the prompt transmittal of transaction documents, such as cash/check disbursement vouchers, etc. together with complete supporting documents, to the Accounting Office for recording and timely submission to the Office of the COA Auditor for post-audit and evaluation;

City Accountant to ensure completeness of supporting documents before certifying the claim and allowing its payment. Further, strictly adhere with the provision of COA Circular No. 2009-006 on submission of reports, accounts and transaction documents for post-audit to timely determine the regularity and validity of the transaction and correctness of the reported account balances.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Head of the General Services Office to (a) cause the preparation of the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property together with the corresponding assessment, evaluation and appraisal reports; 

(b) facilitate the submission of request for disposal of said PPEs to the Office of the Auditor for inspection, evaluation and review by the COA Technical Services Office; 



(c) undertake immediate disposal of the subject properties to prevent further deterioration, decline of value and in order to generate additional funds from sale thereof after receipt of favorable COA recommendation on the submitted request; and 

(d)  require the GSO to prepare and submit the regular schedule of disposal of assets once the same became unserviceable and beyond economical repairs to avoid the accumulation of unserviceable PPEs in the storage facility and to prevent the recurrence of similar lapses.

We recommended and management agreed that (a) the LCPC/CCWPC submit the reports and documents  required under DILG MC No. 2008-126 and DILG MC No. 2012-120, respectively; 

(b) the CSWD and City Budget Officer to adhere with the provisions of RA 9344, on the required allocation of the amount equivalent to 1% of IRA for the purpose; and 

(c) conduct timely planning and implementation of the programs, projects and activities for the child protection and development to efficiently deliver the services to the intended beneficiaries.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (a) direct the Head of the City Economic Enterprise and Public Utilities and Management Office (CEEPUMO) (i) to coordinate with the City Legal Office for the issuance of the necessary follow up/ demand letters to the accountable delinquent stall holders/occupants for the settlement of delinquent accounts; 

(ii) initiate legal action, if warranted, to collect the long overdue arrearages; and 



(iii) strictly enforce the provisions of the contract/agreement in order to prevent the recurrence of similar problem in the future; 



(b) require the CEEPUMO to facilitate the submission of an updated master list of stallholders and reconcile the same with the actual occupants and numbers of market stalls appearing in the structure layout plan of the two markets to clearly establish that all units are properly accounted, recorded and included in the monthly report of market collections and prevent the re-leasing of the stalls.

We also recommended that management revisit the rental rates on market stalls/space and consider the possible adjustments to an equitable  level and  comparable with the prevailing current rates being adopted in the locality.

We recommended and management agreed that the (i) CGSO  strictly comply with the required maintenance of complete and updated PPELCs and PCs, respectively for each class of property and to record the acquisition, adjustments and disposal thereof; (ii) Inventory Committee exert extra effort to complete the pphysical inventory of all property, plant, and equipment of the City Government and reconcile the report with the accounting records; and (iii) observe the consistent submission of the physical inventory reports on PPEs to the Office of the Auditor for review and validation not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to existing rules and regulations;
Moreover, the City Accountant, City Assessor and Heads of the General Services Office (GSO) and City Planning and Development Office (CPDO) (i) coordinate with each other and reconcile their records to ascertain the correctness of the Land account balance; and (ii) facilitate the registration in the name of City Government the parcel of lots acquired which were not yet covered by TCT to preclude third party claims over said properties;
Finally, we recommended that the Accounting Office recognize in the books of accounts all unrecorded parcels of land acquired by the City and maintain Real Property Ledger Card for each and every parcel of land/PPEs owned by the City.

In view of the foregoing lapses, we recommended and management agreed that the City Mayor:
require the officials of the Farmers’ Association/Cooperatives to initiate coordination with the owners of the lots where the MPDP were constructed to discuss the possible donation/transfer of the parcel of land used in the project in favor of the government;
ensure that the requirement on ownership of land, by the City Government, where the project will be constructed must first be met before its implementation in order to avoid occurrence of similar deficiency;
instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and BAC Secretariat to strictly observe the required posting of Notices in the PhilGEPS website within the period as prescribed under Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of IRR of RA No. 9184; and
remind the City Accountant to (i) cause the immediate submission of the required supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor for review and evaluation; and (ii) strictly adhere to the fundamental principles in the disbursement of funds prescribed under Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445 on the submission of complete documentation for every claim against government funds to avoid the recurrence of similar lapses.

In view of the foregoing lapses, we recommended and management agreed that the City Mayor :
instruct the City Accountant to cause the immediate submission of the required supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor for review and evaluation in accordance with the fundamental principles in the disbursement of funds prescribed under Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445;
remind the City General Services Officer (GSO) to (a) strictly observe regulation on submission of Notice of Delivery, together with copy of Delivery Receipt and duly accomplished/signed Inspection and Acceptance Report, to the Office of the COA Auditor as required in Section 6.06 of COA Circular 95-006 dated May 18, 1995; and (b) ensure that items are timely distributed to identified beneficiaries/recipients;
instruct the Bids and Awards Committee to observe the timely preparation of the necessary bidding documents to avoid delay in the initiation of the procurement proceedings;
ensure coordination among officials involved in planning, execution and monitoring of the PPAs to achieve the desired outcomes; and
facilitate the awarding/distribution of the subject farm machineries and equipment to the identified recipients in order to efficiently use the equipment and farm machineries and to attain the projected benefits that can be derived therefrom by the farmers.

We recommended that management require the (a) CGSO to strictly comply with the required maintenance of complete and updated PPELC and PC, respectively for each class of property and to record the acquisition, adjustments and disposal thereof; 

(b) Inventory Committee exert extra effort to complete the physical inventory of all property, plant, and equipment of the City Government and reconcile the report with the accounting records; and 

(c) GSO observe the consistent submission of the physical inventory reports on PPEs to the Office of the Auditor for review and validation not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to existing rules and regulations; 

Moreover, the City Accountant, City Assessor and Heads of the General Services Office (GSO) and City Planning and Development Office (CPDO) (a) coordinate with each other and reconcile their records to ascertain the correctness of the Land account balance; (b) facilitate the registration in the name of City Government the parcel of lots acquired which were not yet covered by TCT to preclude third party claims over said properties; and (c) the Accounting Office to record in the books of accounts all unrecorded parcels of land acquired by the City and maintain Real Property Ledger Card for each and every parcel of land/PPEs owned by the City.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office to (i) strictly monitor the timely implementation of the approved programmed plans and activities identified in the LDRRM Plan for the maximum utilization of the LDRRM Fund in order to achieve the target accomplishment for the year;

(ii) ensure that all implemented programs/projects and activities charged to LDRRMF were in line with the LDRRM Plan; and 



(iii) formulate programs and activities strictly in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 and Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 for proper allocation and utilization of LDRRMF.

We recommended and management agreed that the GAD Focal Person continue to (i) develop and implement more GAD related programs/activities that advocate women empowerment, promote gender equality and improve welfare of women that will protect their rights; 

(ii) exert more diligence in identifying priority programs/projects during the planning and budget preparation to avoid sacrificing the implementation of priority programs; and 

(iii) strictly adhere to PCW-NEDA-NCRFW Joint Circular No. 2004-01 in the implementation of planned projects.

We recommended and management agreed that the City Solid Waste Management Board (CSWMB) and the Environmental Protection Division (EPD) (i) exert effort to expedite the establishment and completion of the Integrated Solid Waste Management Facility; 

(ii) involve closely the Barangay officials in the strict implementation of the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign on the “no segregation, no collection policy and the “no-littering policy” among the residents; and 



(iii) exercise strong political will to implement the environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment as mandated under Republic Act  No. 9003.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and management agreed that:
The Local School Board, thru the Schools Division Superintendent, (a) give justification for requiring the 30/31 workdays of the JOs; 

(b) ensure that the requirements of PD No. 143 dated March 3, 1973 and other regulations relevant to the hiring of JOs are observed;

The respective school heads/principals provide competent documents that would corroborate their certifications on the number of days worked involving Saturdays, Sundays and Holidays; 

The Schools Division Superintendent direct the school principals concerned to keep, maintain records of the job order individuals assigned or detailed in their respective schools, such as the daily attendance log book and record of daily accomplishments. Utilize the same as reference in checking the correctness of the reports of attendance and accomplishments being submitted by the subject workers; and

Refrain from charging against Special Education Fund the wages of job orders performing clerical/office works in order not to deprive the funding of other legitimate SEF priority programs/projects.

We recommended and management agreed that the LCE remind the GSO to (a) strictly observe the submission of Notice of Delivery, together with copy of Delivery Receipt and duly accomplished/signed Inspection and Acceptance Report, to the Office of Auditor within 24 hours upon receipt of items delivered by the supplier pursuant to COA Circular No. 95-006 dated May 18, 1995; and 

(b) adopt improvement measures, such as systematic pre-delivery repacking of commodities by the supplier to ensure that procured commodities will be timely and completely distributed to the intended beneficiaries in order to effectively serve its purpose.  

We also recommended that the CSWD Officer a) strictly observe the provisions stated in the specific implementing agreement on Supplemental Feeding Program; 

b) explain in writing the discrepancies noted on the duplication and/or simultaneous appearance of names of several beneficiaries in the weighing monitoring report under two different barangays for the same period; 

c) conduct post-evaluation and validation and submit the corresponding reports; and c) coordinate with the BAC, GSO and Accounting Office for the immediate submission of the lacking documents to fully comply with the documentary requirements.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (a) require the CSWDO and the City Accountant to (i) strictly adhere to the fundamental principles in the disbursement of funds prescribed under Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445; and 

(ii) observed full compliance with the requirements consistent with the guidelines of the DSWD in the implementation Cash for Work for Climate Change  Adaption and Mitigation Program; 

b) direct the Social Worker assigned to (i) explain in writing the deficiencies noted particularly on the questionable signatures of claimants appearing in the logbook and the discrepancies of names indicated between the logbook and the corresponding payroll ; and 

(ii) and  ensure that only the persons who actually rendered services be included in the payroll to guarantee that only the rightful claimants will be benefited under the program. 

We likewise recommended and management agreed that the CSWD and Accounting Offices facilitate the immediate submission of lacking documents to the Office of the Auditor, to wit:

Cash for Work Vouchers of the respective claimants/beneficiaries;

 Certificate of Indigency and Residency duly certified by the respective Punong Barangay;

Copy of the Unified MOA entered into by and between the City Government and DSWD pertinent to the subject program; and

Validated accomplishment reports together with the necessary pictures taken during the actual implementation of the program.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local 
Chief Executive direct the City Accountant and City Treasurer to:
continue to strictly observe the rules and regulations governing the withholding and remittance of taxes, premium contributions, etc. with the BIR, GSIS, PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG;



 regularly coordinate to facilitate processing of documents necessary to support the completeness of remittance, recording of transactions and timely transmission of disbursement vouchers to the respective Offices concerned; 



exert efforts in identifying the nature of the previous years’ balances due to GSIS and PhilHealth and make the necessary adjustment/reconciliation thereof to facilitate the immediate remittance of the same to the concerned agencies; and 



coordinate with the City Hospital Administrator for the submission of necessary documents to facilitate the processing and release of professional fees of medical doctors who rendered services therein.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended and management agreed that:
The Local School Board, thru the Schools Division Superintendent, (a) give justification for requiring the 30/31 workdays of the JOs; (b) ensure that the requirements of PD No. 143 dated March 3, 1973 and other regulations relevant to the hiring of JOs are observed;
The respective school heads/principals provide competent documents that would corroborate their certifications on the number of days worked involving Saturdays, Sundays and Holidays;
The Schools Division Superintendent direct the school principals concerned to keep, maintain records of the job order individuals assigned or detailed in their respective schools, such as the daily attendance log book and record of daily accomplishments. Utilize the same as reference in checking the correctness of the reports of attendance and accomplishments being submitted by the subject workers; and
Refrain from charging against Special Education Fund the wages of job orders performing clerical/office works in order not to deprive the funding of other legitimate SEF priority programs/projects.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive (a) require the CSWDO and the City Accountant to (i) strictly adhere to the fundamental principles in the disbursement of funds prescribed under Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445; and (ii) observed full compliance with the requirements consistent with the guidelines of the DSWD in the implementation Cash for Work for Climate Change  Adaption and Mitigation Program; b) direct the Social Worker assigned to (i) explain in writing the deficiencies noted particularly on the questionable signatures of claimants appearing in the logbook and the discrepancies of names indicated between the logbook and the corresponding payroll ; and (ii) and  ensure that only the persons who actually rendered services be included in the payroll to guarantee that only the rightful claimants will be benefited under the program.
We likewise recommended and management agreed that the CSWD and Accounting Offices facilitate the immediate submission of lacking documents to the Office of the Auditor, to wit:
Cash for Work Vouchers of the respective claimants/beneficiaries;
Certificate of Indigency and Residency duly certified by the respective Punong Barangay;
Copy of the Unified MOA entered into by and between the City Government and DSWD pertinent to the subject program; and
Validated accomplishment reports together with the necessary pictures taken during the actual implementation of the program.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local 
Chief Executive direct the City Accountant and City Treasurer to:
continue to strictly observe the rules and regulations governing the withholding and remittance of taxes, premium contributions, etc. with the BIR, GSIS, PhilHealth and Pag-IBIG;
regularly coordinate to facilitate processing of documents necessary to support the completeness of remittance, recording of transactions and timely transmission of disbursement vouchers to the respective Offices concerned;
exert efforts in identifying the nature of the previous years’ balances due to GSIS and PhilHealth and make the necessary adjustment/reconciliation thereof to facilitate the immediate remittance of the same to the concerned agencies; and
coordinate with the City Hospital Administrator for the submission of necessary documents to facilitate the processing and release of professional fees of medical doctors who rendered services therein.

We recommended and Management agreed that the 


(i) City Accountant and CGS Officer maintain complete and updated PPELC and PC, respectively for each class of property to record the acquisition, adjustments and disposal thereof; 



(ii) Inventory Committee exert extra effort to conduct complete physical count of all property, plant, and equipment of the City Government by type on annual basis and submit to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year pursuant to existing rules and regulations; 


(iii) City Accountant and City Engineer coordinate with each other to trace the necessary records/documents pertaining to those projects that were still accounted under Construction in Progress for proper recording in the books for a fair presentation of PPE accounts in the financial statements; and 


(iv) City Accountant, City Assessor and Heads of the General Services Office (GSO) and City Planning and Development Office (CPDO) (a) coordinate with each other and reconcile their records to ascertain the correctness of the Land account balance; (b) register in the name of City Government the land which were not yet covered by TCT as proof of ownership of the asset; and (c) the Accounting Office record in the books of accounts all unrecorded parcels of land acquired by the City and maintain Real Property Ledger Card for each land property to contain the necessary information relative thereto.

We recommended and Management agreed that the City Accountant 

(i) follow strictly the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances for a more efficient and effective internal control system;

(ii) ensure that all cash advances are reported on as soon as the purpose for which it was granted has been served and that no cash advances remained unliquidated at the end of the year; 



(iii) continue sending demand letters to the employees and to those who have already transferred to another government agency and who were resigned/retired from the service; and  



(iv) the City Legal Officer, if warranted, apply all possible legal remedies for the settlement of cash advances granted to officials and employees.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Economic Enterprise and Public Utilities Management Officer and the City Treasurer to: 

(i) issue follow-up communications and/ or demand letters to stall occupants for the settlement of their respective delinquent accounts on market rentals;


(ii) initiate legal action, if warranted, to collect the long overdue   arrearages; 

(iii) make a thorough study on the appropriateness of the rental rates being charged by  the City as compared with the current prevailing rental rates; 

(iv) justify and support recommendation for the enactment of appropriate Market Code or any ordinance by the Sanggunian for the market rental rate adjustment; and  


(v) effect the execution and/or renewal of lease contract/agreement, if necessary, between the City Government and the stall occupants.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Accounting Office and the CALMO ensure that the utilization of fund transfer from the National Government Agencies is adequately documented for proper implementation of the project and submit the following documents to determine as to whether the funds were utilized for its intended purpose:

Validated Master List of the proposed participants to the training, indicating their names and their respective barangays;

Duly verified/certified attendance of participants who actually attended the trainings;

Pictures or other visual evidences that the trainings were conducted;

Accomplishment reports of the trainors in every training conducted, indicating the dates of the trainings, the topic/s discussed and the number of days of training rendered by each trainor/lecturer; and

Basis of determining the rates of honoraria paid to trainors/lecturers.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive require the Accounting, Engineering and Property Officials to strictly adhere to complete documentation of financial transaction of the City and submit the following documents for further evaluation/ verification by the audit team:

Written request by the Head of the schools for the needed materials;
 Dated Program of Works;
Pre-repair inspection report stating the scope of repairs to be done; 
Fully accomplished Inspection and Acceptance Report on the materials delivered; and
Accomplishment reports and pictures before, during and after the repair;
 Inventory reports of scrap materials, if any.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Accounting Office and the CALMO ensure that the utilization of fund transfer from the National Government Agencies is adequately documented for proper implementation of the project.  Likewise, submit the following documents to determine as to whether the funds were utilized for its intended purpose:
Validated Master List of the proposed participants to the training, indicating their names and their respective barangays;
Duly verified/certified attendance of participants who actually attended the trainings;
Pictures or other visual evidences that the trainings were conducted;
accomplishment reports of the trainors in every training conducted, indicating the dates of the trainings, the topic/s discussed and the number of days of training rendered by each trainor/lecturer; and
Basis of determining the rates of honoraria paid to trainors/lecturers.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive require the Accounting, Engineering and Property Officials to strictly adhere to complete documentation of financial transaction of the City and submit the following documents for further evaluation/verification by the audit team:
Written request by the Head of the schools for the needed materials;
Dated Program of Works;
Pre-repair inspection report stating the scope of repairs to be done;
Fully accomplished Inspection and Acceptance Report on the materials delivered; and
Accomplishment reports and pictures before, during and after the repair;
Inventory reports of scrap materials, if any.

We reiterated our recommendations and Management agreed that the City Accountant 

(a) follow strictly the provisions of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 on the granting and utilization of cash advances for a more efficient and effective internal control thereon; 

(b) ensure that all cash advances are reported on as soon as the purpose for which it was granted has been served and that no cash advances remained unliquidated at the end of the year; 



(c) continue sending demand letters to the employees that have already been transferred to another government agency and to those who were retired from the service; and 

(d) the City Legal Officer apply all possible remedies for the settlement of cash advances granted to officials and employees and institute possible legal action against the officials concerned.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) assess the need to engage in consultancy services; 



(b) justify the contracts of the consultants whose services were only duplication of the functions of regular employees or whose works could be performed by existing plantilla personnel; 

(c) in case there is really a need for consultants, engage only experts in their respective fields; 

(d) observe rules and regulations on the hiring of consultants; and 



(e) ensure that payments for consultancy services are supported with adequate documentation.



We further recommended that the 

(a) City Accountant record the honoraria for consultants under Consultancy Services and submit complete documents to support payments; and 

(b) the City Human Resource Officer update the Curriculum vitae of the consultants as regards to their work experience, training and eligibility for ready reference.

We recommended that the City Solid Waste Management Board (CSWMB) and the Environmental Protection Division (EPD) 

(a) exert effort to expedite the establishment and completion of the Integrated Solid Waste Management Facility; 

(b) involve closely the Barangay officials in the strict implementation on the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign on the “no segregation, no collection policy and the “no-littering policy” among the residents by exercising strong political will to implement the environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment as mandated under Republic Act  No. 9003.
